properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Northwesterly winds gusting 80 km/h tonight into Saturday. A fast moving clipper system crossing the prairies will bring gusty winds to southern Saskatchewan through Saturday. Increasing southerlies today will switch to strong northwesterly winds gusting 80 km/h tonight continuing into Saturday. The southeastern corner of the province is expected to receive the strongest winds; additional wind warnings may be required as the system develops. Winds will gradually diminish from west to east throughout Saturday, with most areas returning to light winds by Saturday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-31T10:39:41-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snow likely Saturday and Saturday night. Snow is forecast to begin Saturday morning and continue for most areas into Saturday night. However, from Webequie to Attawapiskat and south, the snow is expected to transition over to a period of rain late Saturday afternoon or Saturday evening. After this period of rain, snow will redevelop Saturday night before easing Sunday morning. At this point in time, forecast guidance suggests 10 centimeters of new snowfall can be expected by the time the snow comes to an end. However over northern areas where the precipitation will remain entirely as snow, up to 15 centimeters can be expected. This heavy snow is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track across northern Ontario Saturday and Saturday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-10-31T07:20:41-00:00

properties.Title: High Wind Effect Alert Issued For The South Basin Of Lake Manitoba And Lake Winnipeg
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a high wind-effect warning for the south basin of Lake Manitoba, the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg. High winds are forecasted to develop overnight Friday October 30th and lasting until early morning Sunday November 1st. Forecasted wind from the northwest gusting up to 90km/h and wave action could raise levels by as much as five feet or more. Be watchful as these winds can result in significant and forceful wave action on shorelines. Property owners in the affected area should take all necessary precautions to stay safe.
Expires: 2020-11-01T06:00:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2020-10-30T13:13:46-05:00, 1154A5B3-C65B-17E4-E47E-C455F0A01FE5
Area: South shores of Lake Winnipeg, and for the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snow Saturday and Saturday night for areas north of Webequie. Snow is forecast to begin Saturday morning and continue into Saturday night. For areas near and south of Webequie, the snow is expected to transition over to a period of rain late Saturday afternoon. After this period of rain, snow will redevelop Saturday evening before easing overnight. Near 10 centimeters of new snowfall can be expected for areas near and south of Webequie while further north, up to 15 centimeters can be expected. By Saturday night, very strong northerly winds gusting up to 70 km/h will also develop, leading to reduced visibilities in blowing snow at times. This heavy snow is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track across northern Ontario Saturday and Saturday night. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Armed Suspect - New Glasgow, Nova Scotia
properties.Summary:
Description: Police are asking for residents in the area of Hillcrest Ave, Norma Street and Mount Baton Drive to hold and secure in their homes until further notice. Police are on scene of Hillcrest Ave, New Glasgow of a report of a suspect with a firearm who is barricaded in an apartment on Hillcrest Ave. Police have the area contained and have closed the area of Hillcrest Ave Norma Street and Mount Baton Drive to motorists and pedestrians. The public are asked to avoid the area. New Glasgow Academy school as a precaution have been placed in a hold and secure.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at times heavy Saturday. Snow at times heavy, is expected to begin tonight and then persist through the day on Saturday. However, areas southeast of Sandy Lake and Summer Beaver are forecast to transition to rain Saturday afternoon, before snow redevelops Saturday evening. Snowfall totals in the 15 to 25 cm range can be expected by the time the snow tapers to flurries Saturday night or early Sunday morning. Snowfall totals are likely to be less than 15 cm in areas that transition to rain. Strong winds gusting up to 60 km/h will also accompany the snow Saturday and Saturday night resulting in reduced visibilities in blowing snow at times. This snow event is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track eastwards across northern Ontario Saturday and Saturday night. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Northwesterly winds gusting 90 km/h Saturday. A fast moving clipper system crossing the prairies will bring severe winds to southeastern Saskatchewan Saturday. Increasing northwesterly winds will develop tonight and by Saturday morning gusts of 90 km/h or more are expected. The severe winds will continue into the afternoon hours before diminishing late in the day. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
